sessions.description:
I was in VivoCity for food, so I thought why not, let’s try walking on that seaside hiking trail. The view was awesome, highly recommended. A good place to view sunset. Don’t take this route at night though if you are scared of the dark.

Didn’t walk all the way to Pasir Panjang MRT where I lived because I was a bit sick on that day.

This trip was when I decided to start this walk-on-CCL project. “Soft-skipped” Haw Par Villa MRT however, since if I went there, I would have to walk a long detour to reach Kent Ridge MRT.

500m was spent when I walked the wrong way on Dover Road.
Went from my place of residence near Pasir Panjang MRT to the Fairprice near Labrador Park MRT to buy milk. Literally. I bought two litres of milk on this day.

Wanted to reach Caldecott MRT in this section, but a heavy rain came right when I was near Botanic Gardens MRT, so I just called it a day and went there instead. A rare time that I ended the walk when the sky was still bright.

It was honestly a very challenging section, because there wasn’t a lot of houses around and Google Maps got me inside the cemeteries here. The path Google Maps told me, by which I would reach the unconstructed Bukit Brown MRT, wasn’t even cemented, and it was already dark then, so I just went ahead and got out of the cemetery to continue on Lornie Highway.

Now thinking back, I should’ve just followed Lornie Highway all the way, and I would’ve got to Marymount MRT in 5km rather than Caldecott MRT in 7km.

The chicken rice at Adam Food Centre was very yummy, by the way.

First day of the new year.

Took this section before continuing from Caldecott MRT because I wanted to see the MBS Drone Show that would take place at 8pm the same day. While the sidewalk was wide, there were a lot of traffic lights and the section near MBS was expectedly incredibly crowded with tourists.

At Marina Square (Esplanade MRT – Promenade MRT), the sidewalk seemed to not exist (?) and I somehow found myself walking inside a shopping mall like a lost man. It was hot outside and the mall was air conditioned, so it was not so bad after all.

Second day of the new year. Thankfully I still managed to find chicken rice when I passed by Bishan.

Planned to turn left to Upper Serangoon Road to get to Serangoon MRT as the destination, then take NEL to get home, but since Bartley MRT isn’t that far away, decided to continue straight ahead on Bartley Road for Bartley MRT instead.

The trip with probably one of the latest starting time and ending time in the entire project. I planned to only finish in Paya Lebar MRT but when I passed it, I thought it was still early so why not continue.

Wanted to even finish the entire CCL by going straight to Promenade MRT but it was 10:40pm when I reached Mountbatten MRT and I decided to end here because I didn’t know if I could finish the next three stations before CCL closing time.

The section from Paya Lebar MRT doesn’t follow roads but instead a park connector along Geylang River. This is part of my favourite biking path in Singapore, which goes from Paya Lebar MRT, along the left side of the river, to reach Marina Barrage and Gardens by the Bay MRT.

Rochor Road unexpectedly did not have a pedestrian path from the other side of Nicoll Highway, so had to go inside Suntec City and get lost there. The second mall in the project, the first that was intentional.

Dropped by Golden Mile Food Centre for dinner.

CCL is completed other than the CCL6 that is still under construction.

Completed the circle, two years ahead of LTA. Hey LTA, I gave you a 22 year head start and still beat you :)

The track mainly follows MCE and AYE, damn expressways. Though, fortunately, AYE is a viaduct so it was still possible to follow it on the ground as a pedestrian. So other than some slight detours for MCE, it was quite easy to plan the path.

I feel CCL6 is mainly for people who want to travel to CBD from CCL on the HarbourFront side rather than for people travelling from and to the three stations on the way, because there’s a giant port here and not many residential or recreational places. Perhaps when the ports move to Tuas, things will change. We will see.

And poor placement for Singapore Art Museum. It’s really not accessible by trains, which definitely significantly impacts its visitor count. But when CCL6 is done, the old railway station and SAM will get a lot more visitors and public interests. Hopefully.

First trip on NEL. Apple Map had me walk on grass by the exit ramp of AYE for a good while. It wanted me to touch some grass maybe. Not sure if I broke any laws by walking like that, my apologises if I did.

Had dinner in Chinatown. Most food stalls are closing at 6:45pm when I was in the food court, so I decided to have Vietnamese food in the nearby Vietnamese restaurant instead. S$12.90 for a bún riêu, crazy expensive compared to the same thing in Hanoi, but it was good and the price is expected for a Singaporean restaurant.

Wanted to reach Little India MRT via Fort Canning Park, but that was a hill 😭 and my legs understandably protested. So ended up finishing in Dhoby Ghaut MRT instead.

That was a relatively calm walk, since the line thankfully goes pretty straight and there's road right up above so I just needed to go straight ahead without looking at my map or scrambling for pedestrian paths much.

Passed by Little India and I was amazed at how many jewellery shops there were. Like, maybe 60% of all the shops that I saw were jewellery shops, which is absolutely unreal.

Planned to end at Potong Pasir MRT since it looks like a good midpoint of the whole line (I want to do NEL in 4 sessions), but the road was not hilly and it was pretty easy, so decided to walk until CCL so I could get home without transferring trains.

The remaining section is still too long (about 8.12 km) for one single session, but the two remaining planned sessions will probably be pretty short. Or should I go wild and do the 8 km walk?

Decided to finish NEL within today. Was it a good decision? I’d say yes. But as expected it was tiring as heck. My body ran out of water to convert to sweat before I reached the interchange with TPE.

For some reasons the map tracking app stopped working midway, so the part around Hougang MRT is inaccurate. I fixed the distance count by measuring the distance on Google Maps, but the pace and calories counts are not as accurate as other sessions.

Since the Punggol Coast extension is so short, I decided to also do the Punggol branch of CRL. That would be some 9km, so I decided to go early. It was raining earlier anyway, I was hoping the sun wouldn't be too bad.

That was a horrible decision. The sun showed up immediately after the rain, along with all its burning hot rays. It was really too hot to walk, even with an umbrella, and I was absolutely drained after just one kilometre from the heat. Absolutely never gonna try walking under such a weather again, I could land myself in a heatstroke.

That said, SIT is pretty much still a giant active construction ground. Are both the MRT station, the bus interchange, and the campus itself, gonna be really ready for use when the institute moves there this autumn? I can't even see any MRT station entrances.

Initially planned to go through Republic Poly, but the gate was closed so I just assumed the campus wasn’t open to the public and so took the loooong detour to Admiralty Road. I think this detour made the trip at least 30% longer.

A portion of Admiralty Park being closed certainly didn’t help make the detour shorter.

I probably could have just asked a nearby student if the campus was open, then went to security to get myself the shortcut, but the trip was planned to be short anyway so the detour is fine. That said, coming to the southern gate of the polytechnic, I noticed the campus might be open to the public after all. The gates and fences were nowhere to be found, compared to the gate neat Woodlands North MRT.

The next trip is gonna be hard. The distance between Woodlands South MRT and Springleaf MRT is really long and I’m expecting myself to go deep into Ulu Sembawang Park. Any obstacles happen and I could be sent back all the way to Woodlands South MRT.

Holy cow. Well, I don’t think I will do a 10km+ session again during this project.

Initially planned to finish in Springleaf MRT, but had a good meal and two Milo’s near the station, and it was still bright then, so decided to continue to Lentor MRT. My legs were mayday’ing as I went into the final kilometre.

Walking with a Protected Area (Mandai Depot) to the left and a military training area to the right was certainly fun. Thankfully I decided to start earlier than usual (thanks weather), since the park connector is not illuminated.

The view of Upper Seletar Resevoir Lake was awesome. Will come back there again. There were no water stations or vending machines nearby though which was unfortunate.

I don’t think I will have another session where I cross an expressway (SLE) three times like this one.

The burning Phuket probably affected the way my body sweats, because just 1km into the session and I was already sweating drops of water all over my face. The entire session was a lot more sweaty than average.

Thankfully my leg still remembered how to walk after the one week break, because I only needed to rest once (for that sweating, 1km in) throughout the entire session.

The stretch between Caldecott MRT and Orchard MRT, especially the stretch from Newtons MRT, is probably the richest area in Singapore. Tons of luxury hotels and apartments. And not a single food court, to the dismay of my screaming stomach.

Planned to finish at Orchard MRT, but it was still relatively early at the time, and my leg was still good, so decided to extend until Outram Park MRT.

Thankfully it didn’t rain during the entire session. The weather had been very cloudy and it looked like it could rain any time for the whole day.

Hurray, that’s TEL finished. Until a few months later when more stations are opened east of Gardens by the Bay MRT…

While this session was relatively short (compared to recent sessions), I was caught in the rain multiple times… The session also went over downtown streets which meant traffic light junctions were everywhere, so there were a lot of breaks.

Marina Mall was closed for some construction project so there was one weird detour near the closed Marina South MRT, as I attempted to walk on that road but failed.

The pedestrian sidewalk to the south of Marina Gardens Drive was absolutely creepy. It was not illuminated, the ground was filled with fallen leaves and there were animals jumping around in the dark. The rain and my fear of snakes didn’t help at all. Ah well, I still got out of it intact.

The first session on under-construction sections of the MRT system. As expected, a… lot of things were under construction and it was quite hard to get past some sections that should have been easy to breeze over. Especially around Marine Parade MRT – there were construction zones everywhere; was the station even completed as reported by the news yet?

GBTB East was magnificent as ever, but at the same time, crowded as ever. They were putting up illustrations of the future memorial, it looks really nice – more green space!

Meyer Road was really quiet, perhaps one of the most peaceful and quiet roads that the MRT system directly goes through. There were barely anyone or anything on the road except some cars passing by. While that may sound chill, to my unpleasant surprise there wasn’t any convenience stores either. I heavily depended on these stores to stay hydrated, so not a single drop of water from GBTB MRT until Marine Parade MRT really fried my throat. Bring enough water guys.

Food at Marine Parade was lovely.

Why did they build the two Marine stations so long and so close to each other… I could swear the gap between the edges of the stations was shorter than either of the stations themselves. Of course, this led to long construction-induced detours. *Very* long detours.

The pedestrian shortcut named “Coastline of Singapore (1969)” on OpenStreetMap connecting Marine Parade Road and Bayshore MRT was very nice. It was not illuminated though, so it was a bit scary. And it does have some stairs so if I cycled instead of walked, I would have probably taken the detour via Upper East Coast Road.

Since the TEL5 stretch is so short, I decided to also do DTLe today. For ease of management, I still recorded it as two separate sessions, though they were done in the same evening.

Eastwood (west of Sungei Bedok) is so peaceful. Family houses, a food centre a short distance away, Bedok Park Connector right next door. When Sungei Bedok MRT opens, it's gonna be a really nice place to live in. Though it's pretty painfully obvious that house prices there are through the roof.

If only I could gain access to the golf courses, going from Sungei Bedok MRT to Xilin MRT would be a lot easier. But thanks to the massive East Coast Integrated Depot, it looks like the only publicly accessible pathway between the two (future) stations is this giant detour that even touches the EWL, for the foreseeable future. Sadie, but what can I do. A good opportunity to try Bedok Park Connector, I'd say.

And how can people in Changi Business Park even work and do business? It's so incredibly noisy there whenever a plane lands – I doubt I could concentrate under such conditions.

It was a very pleasant day today. I found that in a happy day, even when Apple Weather told me there would be no rain causing me to be soaked in light rain the entire way, my mood would still not be dampened.

The track today was pretty easy, there weren’t many traffic light crossings, so I didn’t have to stop for red light a lot of times. There weren’t many turns either, so I didn’t have to stop to look at the map. I think that partially contributed to my pace today, as this is the first time I reached sub-11 pace – my slowest kilometre is still higher than all averages of previous sessions. Wow. Not sure if I can keep up with this pace in future sessions – to get any faster I think I would have to run rather than walk.

Former Bukit Timah Fire Station was not lighted and the buildings looked unmaintained, so in the dark it looked a bit scary. But the pedestrian sidewalk was well illuminated so it was completely fine.

So despite the rain, that was a great start for Downtown Line.

Yesterday it said no rain, didn’t bring umbrella, got soaked in rain the entire session. Today it said there would be rain, brought umbrella, not a single drop of rain appeared. Ah well… The umbrella made it not so easy and comfortable anymore to swing the arms, but dropped by a 7-11 to grab two bottles of drinks (thanks, discount), drank one and used one to counter the weight of the umbrella, so it became comfortable to walk again.

Half the session I had to take detours due to the construction of the North–South Corridor. Construction projects have been the number one cause of unplanned detours in this project.

Things were going well and I wanted to stop in Bayfront MRT, but somehow just when I was approaching Promenade MRT my right foot’s toes started to hurt, so decided to call it a day and stop one station early. Tomorrow I have an exam anyway, it doesn’t hurt to stop earlier than planned.

I said I would not do a 10km+ session again after the TE3–TE5 session on TEL. Well, I just did it again!

Initially I intended to stop at Geylang Bahru MRT, but eventually decided to extend until I reached CCL. Why? I am not under time pressure today (unlike most other days when I have something to do at around 10pm), and I live near CCL.

The session was relatively uneventful, with the roads pretty easy to navigate. However I walked on the wrong side of the road on the exit ramp of PIE near Geylang Bahru MRT. So I lost about 200m there having to turn around to cross the road (you don’t want to jaywalk into vehicles travelling at expressway speed), so that I could use the pedestrian overpass crossing PIE. Lesson learned, be extra careful and never mess with expressways…

That 200m was won back after I found a shortcut via the HDB blocks between Mattar MRT and MacPherson MRT. Really lucky that HDB common grounds are publicly accessible. I should use this trick more.

Another relatively simple session as the line just followed a single road for almost the entire distance. I didn’t have to look at the map for directions until I was about to reach the destination (Tampines MRT). That MRT station is huge though, surprisingly big for a two-line interchange (I guess it’s due to me having to cross a bus interchange as well).

The first one third of the session, I walked alongside a Bangladeshi man. He seems frustrated with his current work and the rising cost of living. All the best to him, though I must admit I couldn’t listen to at least half of what he said because his accent was too heavy for my ears, historically scoring badly in listening tests.

Bedok Reservoir was a bit smaller than I thought. Just a lake and that’s it? Compared to the huge central reservoirs that make my legs protest before I even attempt to hike across them, this one feels too small to be given the reservoir title…
No comments today. Towards the end today has been terrible and I am tired.

Since the TEL5 stretch is so short, I decided to also do DTLe today. For ease of management, I still recorded it as two separate sessions, though they were done in the same evening.

Eastwood (west of Sungei Bedok) is so peaceful. Family houses, a food centre a short distance away, Bedok Park Connector right next door. When Sungei Bedok MRT opens, it's gonna be a really nice place to live in. Though it's pretty painfully obvious that house prices there are through the roof.

If only I could gain access to the golf courses, going from Sungei Bedok MRT to Xilin MRT would be a lot easier. But thanks to the massive East Coast Integrated Depot, it looks like the only publicly accessible pathway between the two (future) stations is this giant detour that even touches the EWL, for the foreseeable future. Sadie, but what can I do. A good opportunity to try Bedok Park Connector, I'd say.

And how can people in Changi Business Park even work and do business? It's so incredibly noisy there whenever a plane lands – I doubt I could concentrate under such conditions.

First impression has to be that the East has a LOT of cycling paths, public space and children playground. Which seems to be partially due to the overground train viaduct, as you cannot build anything under the viaducts so you might as well make them public green space.

The porridge in Pasir Ris Central Hawker Centre is fantastic. A really good way to start the session. The hawker centre was slightly further away from the station than I would like it to, however.

Another thing I noticed is that the gap between stations is quite large. Unlike other newer lines, it takes a lot of time to go from Tanah Merah MRT to Bedok MRT. And I really should have stopped at Tanah Merah MRT. My legs are trembling as I type these lines on a train heading away from Bedok MRT.

Planned to finish at Kallang MRT, but I felt a bit sick. I also observed that even in the first kilometre, I couldn’t maintain the pace I wanted to have, and I would only become slower as I continued further. I also had to take an abnormally long break only 500m in. Considering everything, I decided to end the session VERY prematurely.

I guess, after several days of consecutive long walking sessions, my legs have reached some kind of critical points. Maybe I should take a rest for a few days before continuing again, this time perhaps aiming for City Hall MRT.

After resting and not going to class today, I found myself feeling much better towards the afternoon, so decided to give it a try. And indeed, I was fit enough to continue this project. I only stopped at Lavender MRT because I had something to do at 10pm sharp that I must not miss.

The weather was good and the route was clear. I also faced surprisingly many green lights. That doesn’t excuse me of that moment I stopped a car by walking into the red light once at the Sims Ave–Sims Way junction though. While I genuinely thought it was a zebra crossing at first (and only realised I messed up after that car honked me as I made it halfway), I was still 100% wrong here, and my sincerest apologies to whoever drove that car at that moment.

Another session through downtown and the Central Business District. As expected, and just like countless times I have passed by this place, the trip was filled with traffic light.

Other than that, everyone knows about downtown Singapore already, so I have nothing to add. The weather was nice and Marina Bay was just like the Marina Bay we all know.

Awesome weather these days. Not burning hot, not sunny, but also not a single drop of rain. Just the perfect weather for a long session (reminding me of the Woodlands South MRT – Lentor MRT stretch). A shame I have an exam tomorrow so I cannot continue this until my physical limit is reached.

Leng Kee Road seems to be the car centre of Singapore? Both sides of the road were filled with car shops, from normal cars to very luxurious cars. Some supercars were even parked outside. It was a treat to the eye, though I doubt I’ll ever buy one in the future, when public transportation is this good and the CoE alone could plunge you into bankruptcy.

The dinner at Clementi was surprisingly cheap. Meals typically cost S$5 or more these days in food centres, but the mixed vegetarian rice I got was only S$3.3. It was not bad either… had I known the price in advance I would’ve ordered even more.

When I passed by Jurong East MRT, a guy walked past me at around 7km/h. Just… wow! I thought that was only possible in competitive walking – I tried to keep up in vain, the guy kept breezing forward in ease while my legs crumbled. During this entire project, this is the first time I’ve been overtaken by someone walking when I was already cruising at my top speed. At least, that kinda made me walk faster than usual and we have another sub-11 session after a while.

And… where are the JRL viaducts in Jurong East MRT and Boon Lay MRT? I was looking forward to seeing them but they seemed to just not be built yet.

Wanted to continue from Boon Lay MRT where we left off yesterday, but the weather forecast said there would be a thunderstorm in the West, while the sky in the East would be clear. Changi Airport branch it is, then!

But Changi Airport is NOT accessible on foot at all… To reach the MRT station on foot, I would have to go all the way down to East Coast Park, then walked over to Jurassic Mile, then walked to the airport terminals. Which would cost some 15km… obviously not feasible. So I decided to take this alternative route and finish at a station close to the airport boundary, in lieu of the actual MRT station. It was still 6km+ though… the airport branch sure is long isn’t it?

Walking by Changi Prison is pretty chilling. I think this is the first time I have been this close to a detention center, let alone a state prison.

By the way, the thunderstorms in the West made the sky in the East during sunset absolutely gorgeous. Highly recommended to go to the East on days like this.

Oh GOSH I got soaked in thunderstorm rain the whole time.

Where I live, the sky was crystal clear and the sun was shining brightly when I went to the station. During the entire trip nothing was indicative of any potential rain. But the moment I stepped out of Boon Lay MRT to start the session, rain started pouring down.

At first I thought it would be quick, the sky to the East was still clear anyway, the glowing red sunset was still visible in the horizon. How wrong I was… it only went worse from there.

The entire session was some 100 minutes and only 45 minutes were me walking. The remaining time was spent in sheltered bus stops or under the rail viaduct, for the rain was too heavy for me to even walk under (for reference, the first DTL session was rainy too but it was just light rain so I could still go far).

Planned to reach Tuas Link MRT, so left home early. Then shifted aim to Gul Circle MRT. And eventually Joo Koon MRT.  What choice did I have anyway…

That's EWL done. Wow, the line was so challenging.

I found a technique to significantly make me faster (around 9:30/km pace). It's pretty simple, I just make longer steps… though it is obviously very tiring. I also reduced my step frequency because, well, humans have limits, but even so I was still soaked in sweat about 1km in. So the entire session I just alternated between normal walking and this way of walking. The result? My fastest session yet. I believe if I can keep this up and learn how to walk that way for a long time period, I might have a chance to beat the guy I met at Jurong East in a rematch. Though obviously such a rematch will never come…

EWL from Pioneer MRT no longer has residential areas around it, and from Joo Koon MRT it is basically just port warehouses, shipping companies and the port infrastructure itself. The pros is that traffic lights are less plentiful and the roads are overall pretty empty. The cons is that I really struggled to find a convenience store to get more drinks.

Just a fun fact, but after the train trip home, I now have taken the entire length of the MRT network (excluding LRT). The Joo Koon MRT–Tuas Link MRT stretch was the only stretch I'd never been to until today. This Tuas Link extension is pretty interesting actually, I didn't expect it to just go over another road viaduct, and Gul Circle with its unused platforms was certainly fascinating to see with my own eyes.

We start with the final opened line.

Marina South Pier MRT was still as empty as ever. I wonder if there will ever be a time that the station becomes busy. Even when there are residential projects in Marina South, I suspect people will utilise Marina Bay MRT and Marina South MRT instead of this one which is too far into the coastline.

Tried to avoid Orchard Road because there are a lot of people there, slowing me down. But literally all traffic lights in the area pointed me away from Somerset Road into Orchard Road… so walking directly through the heart of Orchard it is, then.

It is the 14th day in a row that I have a session, and I believe in all but one of them, I walked a substantial distance. Today, my legs finally felt that, probably it would be a good idea to stop the streak at 14 days.

Me having 9 hours worth of class earlier in the day certainly didn't help, ha. The 11:21 pace is relatively worse than recent sessions, but considering everything, I'm surprised I could even go faster than 5km/h on average. When I reached Bishan, I felt the same way I did when I completed the 11km Woodlands South MRT–Lentor MRT stretch on the TEL.

Anyway, this session we concluded the underground part of the (opened) MRT system. The remaining of NSL are all overground! That would make navigating a lot easier.

I passed one expressway and two canals this time, but thankfully bridges are conveniently placed almost exactly where I need them, so I didn't have to go off-course too much.

And what the heck, Newton Food Court? How come you didn't have a single stall selling chicken rice when I came?

Another 10km+ session. It is so refreshing after two days of rest, and my legs functioned very well today.

Today we have another long stretch of no MRT stations, between Yio Chu Kang MRT and Khatib MRT. Thankfully, the MRT line follows a road closely, and the road itself is very pedestrian friendly, despite having a construction project (North South Corridor) along it, so I didn’t have any considerable difficulties in navigating.

That being said, it’s surprising there wasn’t much in the viaduct part of NSC yet. Considering the busy-looking tunnel construction sites, I imagined the viaducts to be a lot more “visible” already – but at the moment there were just a handful of viaduct piers, mainly near the interchange with SLE.

It seemed it was close to the middle of the lunar month. The moon was very bright, and its reflection on Lower Seletar Reservoir was picturesque.

Pace 10:08… holy moly!!! This is definitely my fastest session thus far, and the first time I could maintain 6km/h for an extended period of time (at least 4km). Practice makes perfect I guess, this is the result of hundreds of kilometres of walking over the last 2 months. Still work to be done to beat that Jurong East guy in a potential (hypothetical) rematch, though.

I actually wanted to reach Marsiling MRT, but I started the session later than I wanted, and my time was running out, so decided to stop here. Good luck to myself for the upcoming 9km stretch between Woodlands MRT and Choa Chu Kang MRT. (Will have to skip Yew Tee MRT because there are no bridges connecting it with the Kranji region that don’t require some crazy detours.)

Since the Rail Corridor is not illuminated at night, I decided to reverse the direction for this session so that I could finish the stretch before night falls. That was indeed the right decision, I finished the corridor at Kranji MRT just when the last rays of light from the West were fading away.

I don’t know how I expected the Rail Corridor to be, before I started the trip, but the trail certainly exceeded that expectation. Wide, clean, quiet, straight path, traffic was very light, birds flew by all the way. There were even road signs and kilometre markers, making it feel like a whole expressway for pedestrians and cyclists. Would definitely want to do the remaining 17.9km of the corridor, all the way to Tanjong Pagar Station.

Also, lesson learned: drink tea or water, not milk, on the way. Also don’t be like me and drink like 700ml of milk in one go at Marsiling MRT. Hydration is good but I think I over-hydrated myself at that part.
sessions.start: NS4 JS1 BP1 Choa Chu Kang

sessions.description:
All opened MRT lines are done! Whooh!

I honestly have nothing to say today. Everything was as planned and went normally. Though, honestly, the gaps between stations were a bit bigger than I would expect them to be, considering there are relatively dense residential areas along the track (except the hill between the two Bukit stations).

Next, I will do LRT lines, then maybe, just maybe, I’ll do the under construction sections as well.
sessions.start: NS4 JS1 BP1 Choa Chu Kang

sessions.description:
The CRL challenge has started! Punggol–Punggol Coast was so short I decided to do this stretch on the same day as well.

Although I was getting sick from the heat earlier (see the Punggol Coast session for more details), after one hour or two recovering in a bench with proper hydration, I was well again, enough to do this.

Wanted to go via Lorong Halus Park Connector (which more faithfully follows the line), but I missed the turn in Punggol East, so Pasir Sis Bridge that is! The road was expectedly very busy, but on the flip side there was almost no one on the pedestrian sidewalk so it was not bad. Everything has trade-offs I guess but if you want to cross the river via the red bridge on the park connector, absolutely remember to turn left to Punggol East.

It was surprising to see such big undeveloped land near the river, from the heart of which you would need to go kilometres away to get to any residential places at all. Which would be nice since it was very quiet and empty, if not for the machinery and materials for nearby construction projects – I don't oppose constructions but it's undeniable that the place would look a lot greener and more peaceful without those concrete machines.

Wanted to start at Aviation Park to reach Pasir Ris, but since today is a public holiday, the only bus service to the Aviation Park station site doesn’t operate. Then decided to do the CCNR stretch since today was a rare day where the afternoon was not hot (we remember that CCNR is not illuminated so a night hike is not possible), but alas, it rained – since CCNR is mainly dirt trails, the rain makes it very hard to pass. I was already out of Bright Hill MRT at that time so decided to go to Hougang/Defu instead.

I’m getting fed up with construction zones honestly. The air felt a lot more dusty and hard to breathe, and there were detours everywhere. I really like that more lines are being built, but it must suck for nearby residents who have to put up with it for years.

Was a bit surprised the area around Tavistock MRT was not residential, but instead filled with what looked like industrial warehouses. Of all places, warehouses *there*, so far away from border checkpoints?

Paya Lebar Air Base today. Jammed between a military airbase and two expressways, it was very quiet and chill, as expected. Not a lot of vehicles on the road as well. Overall it was very nice. The forced detour also meant I didn’t have to walk by active construction zones a lot, which is really nice.

A long stretch across CCNR and two (!!) long stretches across two airports. Yeah, the Cross Island Line is certainly a challenge, and I wouldn't rate it as the easiest line to walk on.

Since it crosses the airport, I once again had to take a long detour away from the actual tunnel path. While that means this session is almost 10km for only 4 stations, it actually also means I could avoid active construction zones, and could experience that fresh air. Combined with the breezy wind along the coast, and I got a pretty peaceful walk.

Bus service 35 along the coast was very nice, by the way. One side the airport, one side the sea, the road empty, one bus stop every couple of kilometres. Talk about a smooth ride! It's unfortunate that this bus service only operates in limited hours, and not on Sunday and PH. Bus 35 is surely a hidden gem of Singapore.

CCNR time! Finally, the sky after a few days of rain was dry today, allowing me to hike on dirt trails.

The trails today are part of routes 5 and 6 in the nature reserve, and are both rated as Difficult by NParks. That’s a very fair rating, while the deep forest surrounding the trails meant the sun shine wasn’t as extreme as I would face it outside CCNR, the trails were very hilly. It is very easy to get dehydrated too, do remember to bring a bottle of water (there will be a refill at Ranger Station so don’t worry about water running out, but do bring a bottle and don’t be a dummy like me).

Would I do the trails again? Probably yes, but only with a lot of preparations and only when the weather is really suitable. Otherwise… there are easier hiking tracks out there. Today’s pace being significantly slower than most other sessions is not surprising – you just can’t walk fast or run on these trails.

At least until the alignment of CRL3 is officially confirmed, the CRL challenge is completed! At around 8.5km every session, it was certainly not easy.

Didn’t expect Clementi Road to be that hilly. I wonder how much NP, SIM and SUSS students have to deal with those hills, if they have a lot of slopes and stairs around their campuses then… leg day every weekday I guess.

And I still don’t understand the placement of Jurong Lake District MRT. Why would they put it next to an expressway in the middle of nowhere? If I can afford to travel on the expressway, I wouldn’t be using public transport. Building a station just for bus connections doesn’t make sense. Why not direct the line a bit further south, either make an interchange with the JRL at Pandan Reservoir MRT, or at least put Jurong Lake District MRT near the residential buildings in Teban. Crossing AYE just to build a station and cross AYE again (as part of CRL3, from a leaked alignment in an LTA video) doesn’t make any sense to me.

Despite being an active construction zone, it was surprisingly easy to navigate the roads here. I guess it’s thank to the lines following the roads directly, while there was no road closure to force a detour. The Tengah region is an exception though, roads are not even done there yet so there will be a big hole between Corporation MRT and Choa Chu Kang MRT for the foreseeable future. And PIE is still a giant obstacle, as usual.

I got to see the insanity known as Bahar Junction MRT. I get how it works, but how is it gonna be constructed? An interchange station covering the road in the entire road intersection? As crazy as it sounds, that does seem to be the case, looking at the pillars already built at the intersection.

The 199 out of NTU was really crowded. I was a bit caught off guard, but now that I think about it, I wonder what I even expected… It was a weekday, and 199 was one of the few direct ways for NTU students to commute between Boon Lay MRT and the campus, after all.

And PIE is still a giant obstacle, as usual.

Tengah Town is still a giant construction area just as reported. And barely any roads are open – the road to Tengah MRT is still blockaded, so I had to skip the Choa Chu Kang West–Corporation segment and split JRL2 to two segments. So for JRL2, we have one session that is almost 6km long, and the other not even 1km long. Ridiculous, I know right?

As usual, I still planned the route carefully to minimise the number of traffic light crossings, but this time construction zones took the W. Really, I think I had to deal with twice as many crossings as I initially planned because JRL construction zones kept forcing me to cross the road.

You might have noticed this session started unusually late. I wanted to take a late night bus once just to experience it, so I only left my home at 7:30pm. How did it go? Well, I did take a 11:15pm bus, but it was not completely empty as I expected. And convenience stores all closing down at night while my throat was dying of thirst certainly didn’t help. All things considered, I wouldn’t recommend doing this.
sessions.start: JS1 NS4 BP1 Choa Chu Kang

sessions.label: BPLRT
sessions.description:
Bukit Panjang LRT fully done in one go.

This track is pretty hilly to he honest, though the railroad follows very closely with the roads and pavements below it, so it was pretty easy to navigate. That being said, there are NO pedestrian crossing for the intersection between Woodlands Road and Petir Road, so if you want to do this track, you absolutely have to cross Woodlands Road at the intersection with Bukit Panjang Road. Otherwise you have to U-turn and go through the MRT station to cross the road.

And of course I won’t fail to comment on the fact that this is the fastest session I’ve had so far. Wow… almost 6km/h already, and I could even maintain 9:20 pace in one kilometre of the track. The dude in Jurong East really upped my skills in fast walking, didn’t he? About time I aim for sub-10 pace and maximising at sub-9 (7km/h).
sessions.start: BP1 NS4 JS1 Choa Chu Kang

sessions.label: SKLRT
sessions.description:
Another LRT line done in one go. I initially wanted to do each loop in a separate session, but today I was bored and didn’t want to work, so I went early and had the fourth 10km session! Well… to think I wanted to stop having 10km sessions after my first one, this is surely an achievement.

I didn’t realise Fernvale was that crowded. It honestly felt like a town of its own. Seriously, a two-car Light Rail Transit service is not enough for this. Someone needs to build the Seletar Line to connect Fernvale to CBD as soon as possible, this place is in dire need of its own MRT station.

The food at Food Paradise near the Sengkang Central–Sengkang East Avenue was cheap and Milo was still as delicious as ever. I gotta buy another bag of Milo to bring home when I go back to Vietnam.

sessions.label: PGLRT
sessions.description:
YAYYY… THAT’S ALL OPENED PARTS OF THE MRT/LRT SYSTEM DONE!!

A surprising portion of Punggol is still under construction. Well, many parts of it are already done but still closed to the public. Sentul Walk seems to be done already but still fenced so it was not viable to walk between Sam Kee LRT and Punggol Point LRT. So I had to come up with this track which doesn’t cover the west loop fully. Well, what could I have done anyway.

As an enthusiast of UI design and the MRT system, there was one big bombshell surprise today: Sam Kee LRT exit D has a sign that follows TEL-era design, which is probably the only instance of that design system throughout the LRT network. It was a pleasant surprise.

And near Nibong LRT, there was a fire so big it glowed up the sky. I was initially quite worried, but seeing people not displaying any interests at all and even a firetruck speeding on literally the opposite direction, maybe the fire was intentional and not a cause of concern after all.
